MODULE 2 - ROOM 1 - WHAT IS NETWORKING?
TASK 1 - WHAT IS NETWORKING?
• Network = Two or more connected devices that can communicate and share data.
• Examples: Internet, power grid, transport systems, mobile networks.
• Devices on a network can include computers, phones, servers, routers, cameras, and IoT devices.
• Networking is a fundamental concept in Cyber Security because attackers and defenders operate across networks.
KEY TERM
• Network: A collection of connected devices.
TASK 2 - WHAT IS THE INTERNET?
• Internet = A global network made up of many smaller networks.
• Invented through the evolution of ARPANET (1960s).
• World Wide Web (WWW) was created by Tim Berners-Lee in 1989.
• Networks are classified as:
•	Private Network (Home, Office)
•	Public Network (Internet)
IMPORTANT CONCEPT
• Internet ≠ WWW
• Internet = Infrastructure/Network
• WWW = Websites and web pages running on the Internet
KEY TERM
• WWW (World Wide Web): System used to access websites on the Internet.
TASK 3 - IDENTIFYING DEVICES ON A NETWORK
IP ADDRESS
• IP = Internet Protocol.
• Used to identify a device on a network.
• IPv4 consists of 4 sections called Octets.
• Example: 192.168.1.1
• An IP address can change over time.
PUBLIC VS PRIVATE IP
• Public IP: Visible on the Internet, assigned by ISP.
• Private IP: Used inside local networks.
PRIVATE IP RANGES
• 10.0.0.0 – 10.255.255.255
• 172.16.0.0 – 172.31.255.255
• 192.168.0.0 – 192.168.255.255
IPv4
• 32-bit addressing.
• Supports approximately 4.3 billion addresses.
IPv6
• 128-bit addressing.
• Supports approximately 340 undecillion addresses.
• Created to solve IPv4 exhaustion.
MAC ADDRESS
• MAC = Media Access Control.
• Physical address assigned to a network card(hardware device ).
• Usually permanent and unique.
• Example: a4:c3:f0:85:ac:2d
• Consists of 12 hexadecimal characters.
MAC SPOOFING
• Changing/faking a MAC address to impersonate another device.
• Used in attacks and bypassing poorly configured security systems.
IMPORTANT DIFFERENCE
• IP Address = Logical Address (Can Change)
• MAC Address = Physical Address (Usually Fixed)
KEY TERMS
• IP = Internet Protocol
• MAC = Media Access Control
• Octet = Each section of an IPv4 address
• ISP = Internet Service Provider
TASK 4 - PING (ICMP)
PING
• Network utility used to test connectivity between devices.
• Checks whether a device is reachable.
• Measures response time (latency).
ICMP
• ICMP = Internet Control Message Protocol.
• Used by Ping for communication.
• Uses Echo Request and Echo Reply packets.
COMMANDS
ping 10.10.10.10
ping 8.8.8.8
IMPORTANT USES
• Test network connectivity.
• Troubleshoot network issues.
• Measure network delay.
• Check if a host is online.
KEY TERMS
• ICMP = Internet Control Message Protocol
• Latency = Time taken for data to travel between devices
